The White House Press Secretary, Josh Earnest, held a briefing in which he discussed President Obama's executive actions on gun control. He highlighted the importance of expanding access to mental health care and criticized Republicans for repealing the Affordable Care Act, which has expanded mental health care coverage. Earnest also discussed the preparatory work done by the Department of Justice to anticipate legal challenges to the executive actions. He emphasized that the actions fall within the President's legal authority and expressed confidence in the administration's legal case. Earnest also addressed questions about the President's emotional response to gun violence, the enforcement of background checks, and the political implications of the executive actions. He mentioned other priorities for the President, such as criminal justice reform and economic issues, and hinted at possible campaign involvement in the upcoming election. Earnest also responded to questions on the Iran-Saudi conflict, domestic extremism, and the release of terrorist videos.